<div id="review_157369757" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/157369757" />
    <a title="Ian Pardo" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5155662-ian-pardo"><img alt="Ian Pardo" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1301477747p2/5155662.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/157369757?book_show_action=true">Mar 28, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ian Pardo" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ian Pardo" href="/user/show/5155662-ian-pardo">Ian Pardo</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer157369757" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7889973184661129906">Bernard Malamud&apos;s Pulitzer Prize- and National Book Award-winner is a nightmare rendered masterfully as art. Yakov Bok&apos;s story is that of human dignity, and the search thereof even in the most indignant of circumstances. According to Yakov, if he has a philosophy, it&apos;s that things in this world can be better. <br/><br/>And this perhaps is the book&apos;s greatest legacy. In the insightful foreword by Jonathan Safran Foer, he says that the world is the broken thing and that everyone can be its fixer. And though</span>
  <span id="freeText7889973184661129906" style="display:none">Bernard Malamud's Pulitzer Prize- and National Book Award-winner is a nightmare rendered masterfully as art. Yakov Bok's story is that of human dignity, and the search thereof even in the most indignant of circumstances. According to Yakov, if he has a philosophy, it's that things in this world can be better. <br /><br />And this perhaps is the book's greatest legacy. In the insightful foreword by Jonathan Safran Foer, he says that the world is the broken thing and that everyone can be its fixer. And though good books tell us what is wrong with the world, only great books -- like The Fixer, compel us to do something about it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7889973184661129906" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


